In the course of a study of the mammalian community from the upper zone of the Manu Biosphere Reserve, along the Río Cosñipata Valley, Cusco , Peru in 1989, we captured three specimens of Anoura that were considerably distinct from any other Anoura species known from Peru . Three additional specimens were collected in expeditions from 1995 to 1996 , and 1999 to 2001 , and reported in several papers as Anoura sp. nov. (
Pacheco et al. , 1993
;
Patterson et al. , 1996
;
Solari et al. , 2006
) or Anoura sp. (
Pacheco et al. , 1995
). This new taxon belongs to the A. caudifer complex (sensu Mantilla-Meluk and Baker, 2010) and has a narrow and densely haired uropatagium that closely resembles to A. aequatoris ; but also has several skin and craniodental features that clearly differentiate it from A. aequatoris and other congeners. These differences convince us that the Manu population corresponds to an unnamed species which we diagnose and describe in this work.

